==English==
{{wikipedia|River Yare}}
===Etymology===
Of {{w|Anglo-Celtic}} origin, the name probably means "babbling brook," from a {{der|en|gem|-}} base {{m|gem-pro|*gar|t=noisy, chattering}}, probably related to {{der|en|gem-pro|*karō|t=complaint, moan}} and {{cog|la|garrio|t=to babble, chatter}}.<ref>A History of English Place Names and Where They Came From. (2020). (n.p.): Pen and Sword History, p. 194</ref>
===Pronunciation===
* {{IPA|en|/jɛə(ɹ)/}}
===Proper noun===
{{en-proper noun}}
# {{place|en|river|co/Norfolk|cc/England}}, which flows into the [[North Sea]] at [[Great Yarmouth]].
